1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:05,238
Tonight I want to talk about the fourth noble truth and how it relates to the law of karma.

2
00:00:06,259 --> 00:00:13,169
The fourth truth states that there is a path leading to the end of suffering, the noble eightfold path.

3
00:00:14,271 --> 00:00:16,693
Our injunction is to follow that path.

4
00:00:18,856 --> 00:00:25,567
There is a poem by the Spanish poet Antonio Machada that I find helpful in thinking about the eightfold path.

5
00:00:26,408 --> 00:00:28,670
Here is a very loose translation.

6
00:00:29,225 --> 00:00:31,509
Wayfarer, there is no way.

7
00:00:32,229 --> 00:00:34,332
The way forms as you walk it.

8
00:00:36,316 --> 00:00:39,942
So we can't look ahead and see where the Eightfold Path is taking us.

9
00:00:40,783 --> 00:00:45,110
We can't work out how long till we get to the end or the next milestone.

10
00:00:46,311 --> 00:00:49,156
We can only form the path step by step.

11
00:00:50,993 --> 00:00:55,259
We can think of the eight strands to the path as different parts to each step.

12
00:00:56,301 --> 00:01:04,415
The path is divided into three sections, wisdom, morality and the cultivation of our mind and heart through meditation.

13
00:01:06,158 --> 00:01:10,064
Imagine trying to form a path through a thick jungle.

14
00:01:11,698 --> 00:01:15,962
The strands of wisdom cut through the thicket so we can see more clearly.

15
00:01:16,003 --> 00:01:20,987
We express our wisdom in the world by our speech, actions and livelihood.

16
00:01:21,868 --> 00:01:24,691
This is our step into the clearing we have just hacked out.

17
00:01:26,213 --> 00:01:37,284
Rather than hacking away doggedly at the thicket in front of us, we rest to contemplate our new position, find the most promising route, the easiest branches to fell.

18
00:01:37,822 --> 00:01:41,150
This is the cultivation of heart and mind in meditation.

19
00:01:42,375 --> 00:01:44,239
These sharpen the sword of wisdom.

20
00:01:44,280 --> 00:01:48,691
And so we are ready to cut out the next step.

21
00:01:50,950 --> 00:01:53,853
Each of the eight strands is described as right.

22
00:01:54,355 --> 00:02:01,444
For example, the first section on wisdom has two subdivisions termed right understanding and right attitude.

23
00:02:02,484 --> 00:02:13,599
The word right can stir the judging mind and I think the translations straightened out or disentangled give a better description of what happens as we follow the path.

24
00:02:14,609 --> 00:02:19,979
At first we get caught in tangles of thought when we try to work out how to live well.

25
00:02:21,081 --> 00:02:28,978
But the more we walk the path the more we sense our thought processes straightening out our emotional life disentangling.

26
00:02:30,580 --> 00:02:33,646
We become more straightforward in our dealings with others.

27
00:02:35,382 --> 00:02:47,316
In meditation, we can often feel ourselves getting into knots of tension as the hindrances show up, and then feel the relief as those knots loosen in the light of awareness.

28
00:02:48,712 --> 00:02:57,167
Now, straightened out and disentangled are both a bit of a mouthful, so I'll follow the convention of calling each step right this or that.

29
00:02:58,028 --> 00:03:06,203
But bear in mind the gentler and more evocative sense that we disentangle ourselves from the binds of dukkha as we develop our path.

30
00:03:08,727 --> 00:03:12,173
The first section of the path is right understanding.

31
00:03:13,282 --> 00:03:20,312
This is the polar opposite of avicca, the ignorance that forms the basis for the wheel of conditions ending up in dukkha.

32
00:03:21,474 --> 00:03:34,092
While avicca implies not understanding what causes suffering and what prevents it, this first step in the path leading out of suffering implies understanding those very processes.

33
00:03:35,456 --> 00:03:39,783
Hearing about and reflecting on the Dhamma cultivates right understanding.

34
00:03:41,126 --> 00:03:47,355
But if understanding is confined only to the cognitive level, it can tighten into absolute judgments.

35
00:03:48,337 --> 00:03:51,643
Rules become commands and to break them is treachery.

36
00:03:52,282 --> 00:03:58,711
When cognitive understanding filters in the domain of will and emotion, we take the dhamma to heart.

37
00:03:59,931 --> 00:04:02,256
This is what we mean by right attitude.

38
00:04:03,456 --> 00:04:06,181
This is the second strand to the Eightfold Path.

39
00:04:07,483 --> 00:04:16,634
Wisdom thus has two strands, right understanding, which is mainly cognitive, and right attitude, which means a wise heart.

40
00:04:18,910 --> 00:04:22,636
We often use the word attitude to describe negativity.

41
00:04:23,057 --> 00:04:29,346
We say he or she has an attitude to mean that they go their own way without much considerations for others.

42
00:04:30,468 --> 00:04:36,437
But in fact one can have a friendly attitude and that is what is meant in the second strand of wisdom.

43
00:04:37,779 --> 00:04:42,988
While cognitive understanding tends to tighten the mind, friendliness tends to soften it.

44
00:04:44,071 --> 00:04:46,233
Together they make for a balance.

45
00:04:47,750 --> 00:04:51,274
Enough honest discernment to be able to tell right from wrong.

46
00:04:52,194 --> 00:04:54,497
Enough friendliness to forgive mistakes.

47
00:04:57,021 --> 00:05:00,824
Right attitude emerges naturally as we practice mindfulness.

48
00:05:02,026 --> 00:05:07,432
But we can accelerate the process by also practicing the four Brahma Viharas.

49
00:05:08,995 --> 00:05:13,740
The term Brahma Vihara translates as the abode of the gods.

50
00:05:14,682 --> 00:05:19,689
Metta, usually translated as goodwill or loving kindness, is the first of these.

51
00:05:21,031 --> 00:05:23,596
We wish ourselves and others to be well and happy.

52
00:05:23,636 --> 00:05:32,410
This undermines the aversive habits that cloud our mind, ill will, anger, coldness, fear, etc.

53
00:05:33,672 --> 00:05:40,081
It doesn't uproot the seed in the same way that mindfulness does, but it nulls the aversive effect.

54
00:05:41,158 --> 00:05:50,009
In our gardening analogy, you could say it covers over the weeds, preventing them from getting any sunlight, so they can't thrive and sow more seeds.

55
00:05:51,432 --> 00:05:54,596
The combination of metta and mindfulness is very powerful.

56
00:05:55,716 --> 00:06:04,348
Metta suppresses aversion to help us be more friendly and live in accord with the Dhamma, while mindfulness weeds away at the hindrances.

57
00:06:06,403 --> 00:06:09,269
The second Brahma Vihara is compassion.

58
00:06:10,610 --> 00:06:20,728
As we undermine our habitual aversion to suffering, our hearts show their capacity for compassion and our speech and activities become more caring.

59
00:06:22,132 --> 00:06:31,348
We practice this Brahma Vihara by bringing to mind someone who is having a hard time, could be ourselves, and wishing them to be free from suffering.

60
00:06:33,286 --> 00:06:38,935
The third Brahma Vihara is Mudita, often translated as appreciative joy.

61
00:06:38,975 --> 00:06:47,709
As we undermine fear, jealousy and other aspects of ill will, our hearts are more easily gladdened by good news.

62
00:06:48,889 --> 00:06:59,547
We're not so ready to dismiss our own achievements with a self-deprecating remark like, that was nothing really, but to congratulate ourselves for the effort we made.

63
00:07:00,774 --> 00:07:04,680
And when we hear of another's success, we feel happy for them.

64
00:07:06,202 --> 00:07:23,086
We cultivate this Brahma Vihara by bringing to mind someone who has had good news, again, this can be ourselves, and saying, may your happiness continue, may your happiness increase, or if you prefer, I am happy that you are happy.

65
00:07:25,396 --> 00:07:31,064
While compassion lets us bear the suffering in the world, mudita helps us acknowledge its joys.

66
00:07:32,526 --> 00:07:36,271
Metta forms the basis for both in its cultivation of friendliness.

67
00:07:37,653 --> 00:07:42,742
All three of these Brahmaviharas need the support of the fourth, equanimity.

68
00:07:44,723 --> 00:07:47,408
Equanimity is one of the factors of enlightenment.

69
00:07:48,048 --> 00:07:53,918
Remember the bird with the wide wingspan, steadying the flock through the ups and downs of their journey.

70
00:07:55,298 --> 00:08:03,427
Without equanimity, metta easily overshoots into attachment and we become dependent on our friends for our sense of worth.

71
00:08:04,788 --> 00:08:11,716
With equanimity, we learn to accept that friends have separate lives, other responsibilities, other affections.

72
00:08:13,598 --> 00:08:17,483
Without the balance of equanimity, compassion slides into pity.

73
00:08:18,725 --> 00:08:23,550
What's happening is that we're seeing ourselves as the stronger party caring for the weaker one.

74
00:08:24,154 --> 00:08:27,098
it can become an addiction, needing to be needed.

75
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:37,091
Equanimity restores the balance, lets us see the strength at the core of the other's being, trust to their capacity to heal and recover.

76
00:08:37,130 --> 00:08:47,964
If the person is dying, equanimity helps see this not as a tragedy, but as part of the mystery of life, nothing to pity them for.

77
00:08:49,044 --> 00:08:52,068
After all, our own term will come quick enough.

78
00:08:53,736 --> 00:08:58,582
Mudita escalates into excitement unless it is supported by equanimity.

79
00:08:59,565 --> 00:09:04,731
We latch on to the joy, identify with it and believe life is going to be perfect from now on.

80
00:09:05,673 --> 00:09:10,158
When we inevitably fall from grace, we are shocked and confused, wondering what went wrong.

81
00:09:11,220 --> 00:09:20,773
Equanimity gives us the balance we need to recognise joy as a temporary gift, to enjoy it to the full and then let it go when the time is right.

82
00:09:23,554 --> 00:09:33,188
What we let go into is equanimity, that peaceful balance of mind which knows better than to cling to the good stuff or struggle with the rotten stuff.

83
00:09:34,672 --> 00:09:41,581
The classic phrase used to cultivate equanimity is the reflection, all beings are the owners of their karma.

84
00:09:42,823 --> 00:09:47,571
This reminds us that we have no direct power over our own or others' happiness.

85
00:09:48,832 --> 00:09:56,730
It is designed as an antidote to the delusion of ourselves as a benign deity who can make people happy just by wishing this.

86
00:09:58,232 --> 00:10:06,048
It sounds comical, but in fact it is a delusion easily stirred by practicing with the Brahma Viharas.

87
00:10:06,804 --> 00:10:11,275
Even the term Brahma Vihara, abode of the gods, suggests this.

88
00:10:11,316 --> 00:10:21,961
It feels godlike to have our hearts filled with goodness, kindness, joy, friendliness, as if we are above and beyond the troubles of the world.

89
00:10:21,942 --> 00:10:29,333
In that sublime state, our thoughts of a person being well and happy are easily mistaken as the reality for that person.

90
00:10:30,456 --> 00:10:36,104
The reflection, all beings are owners of their karma, brings us down to earth.

91
00:10:37,105 --> 00:10:38,989
We realize our limitations.

92
00:10:40,554 --> 00:10:45,702
You may be able to find a phrase which carry the same meaning but resonates easier in your heart.

93
00:10:46,364 --> 00:10:52,413
For example, I sometimes use the phrase, I trust you to find your own path to Nibbana.

94
00:10:53,394 --> 00:11:00,706
This helps me to see the other person more objectively and cultivates respect for their separate path in life.

95
00:11:02,610 --> 00:11:11,426
Just as Metta, Compassion and Mudita need equanimity to balance them, equanimity needs the other Brahma-Viharas for its own balance.

96
00:11:11,905 --> 00:11:15,231
Without them, equanimity easily slips into indifference.

97
00:11:16,253 --> 00:11:19,778
We let go of others to such an extent we no longer feel anything for them.

98
00:11:20,500 --> 00:11:26,289
When this happens, it's time to start practising with whichever of the other three is most appropriate.

99
00:11:28,109 --> 00:11:31,613
Right understanding polishes one side of the sword of wisdom.

100
00:11:32,714 --> 00:11:35,056
The Brahm of Ihara is polished the other side.

101
00:11:36,357 --> 00:11:44,386
With this double-edged sword we cut our way through the jungle of hindrances, clearing another step along our eightfold path.

102
00:11:46,448 --> 00:11:54,116
This brings us to the next section of the path, Sila in Pali, usually translated as morality or ethics.

103
00:11:54,839 --> 00:11:57,442
Selah is the expression of wisdom in daily life.

104
00:11:58,484 --> 00:12:05,975
I'm going to use the Pali word Selah because we often associate morality with a strict, joyless approach to life.

105
00:12:07,037 --> 00:12:09,681
Family photos from Victorian times illustrate this.

106
00:12:10,240 --> 00:12:11,102
No one smiles.

107
00:12:11,462 --> 00:12:14,067
The children look miserable in their heavy, awkward suits.

108
00:12:14,727 --> 00:12:21,758
An austere father towers over them while his wife sits demurely at his side, laced and buttoned within an inch of her life.

109
00:12:23,357 --> 00:12:26,664
Desire finds no expression in this picture of morality.

110
00:12:27,466 --> 00:12:30,273
But we need to remember that desire can also be wise.

111
00:12:30,332 --> 00:12:35,043
The desire to be happy is perhaps our most basic drive in life.

112
00:12:36,164 --> 00:12:42,918
It only gets us into trouble because we don't rightly understand what allows for happiness, what causes suffering.

113
00:12:44,350 --> 00:12:49,918
The Buddha promises us that if we follow this path we will be content and therefore happy.

114
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:54,244
Morality in this light is seen as a step towards happiness.

115
00:12:57,227 --> 00:13:02,235
I want to touch on the law of kamma here to clarify the link between morality and happiness.

116
00:13:03,376 --> 00:13:05,780
Kamma is the Buddha's teaching on causality.

117
00:13:06,642 --> 00:13:10,947
He discovered that happiness and unhappiness are governed by the laws of kamma.

118
00:13:12,227 --> 00:13:19,615
When we hear of someone's good fortune, we might say, ah, that's your good kamma showing up, and we might think along the same lines for misfortune.

119
00:13:20,416 --> 00:13:21,496
But this is a mistake.

120
00:13:22,577 --> 00:13:26,360
The Buddha said that kamma was one of five laws operating in the universe.

121
00:13:27,481 --> 00:13:30,105
The first are the laws that govern the physical world.

122
00:13:30,164 --> 00:13:41,475
These, rather than kamma, could be at the basis for lots of common misfortunes, infections, car crashes, etc., as well as major events like earthquakes, drought and hurricanes.

123
00:13:43,125 --> 00:13:49,696
And physical conditions and the laws governing them can bring good fortune, health, strength, a good harvest or good weather.

124
00:13:50,999 --> 00:13:54,403
The second set of laws are the biological laws of heredity.

125
00:13:55,325 --> 00:13:59,731
We may inherit a parent's musical ear or a family gene for heart disease.

126
00:14:00,913 --> 00:14:03,298
The third are the laws that govern our mind.

127
00:14:03,999 --> 00:14:07,664
We might get Alzheimer's and no longer be able to think clearly.

128
00:14:07,644 --> 00:14:11,934
or we may be born with a very high IQ or a talent for languages.

129
00:14:13,097 --> 00:14:14,802
The fourth is the law of Kama.

130
00:14:15,884 --> 00:14:21,979
Finally, there are the laws of Dhamma, that all phenomena are subject to change, ageing and death.

131
00:14:22,860 --> 00:14:26,328
No matter how impeccable our Kama, we will die.

132
00:14:27,996 --> 00:14:32,183
Thus, kamma is only one of five sets of laws governing events in our life.

133
00:14:33,326 --> 00:14:36,751
We cannot ascribe someone's handicap or poverty to bad kamma.

134
00:14:37,393 --> 00:14:41,539
Neither can we ascribe their musical genius or longevity to good kamma.

135
00:14:43,121 --> 00:14:47,710
What we can ascribe to their previous kamma is a person's happiness or unhappiness.

136
00:14:48,672 --> 00:14:52,418
These, the Buddha discovered, operate under the law of kamma.

137
00:14:54,220 --> 00:15:04,118
When we think, speak or act motivated by greed, hatred or delusion, we sow bad karma which will eventually ripen to harm us and diminish our happiness.

138
00:15:05,220 --> 00:15:07,344
Similarly, thoughts of goodwill etc.

139
00:15:07,965 --> 00:15:12,634
sow seeds of karma that will ripen to benefit us and make us happier.

140
00:15:14,756 --> 00:15:26,073
The harm we do ourselves from acting out of ill-will, etc., happens at the point of becoming, bhava, in the wheel of dependent origination that we spoke of last night.

141
00:15:27,635 --> 00:15:36,528
Remember the sankara seeds, our habitual drives, that can germinate and then sprout through our senses to urge us to react to circumstances.

142
00:15:37,572 --> 00:15:48,291
At the point of bhava, our seed has blossomed into a sense of self who is now about to think, act or speak under the influence of this habitual drive.

143
00:15:49,856 --> 00:16:00,029
At the moment the thought, deed or act starts, a seed of that sankara is sown, to sprout at some future time when the opportunity presents itself.

144
00:16:01,292 --> 00:16:10,803
For now, this sankara has come out of potential into action, to give birth to a thought, an act or an utterance that carries out its will.

145
00:16:12,947 --> 00:16:14,869
How does this cause unhappiness?

146
00:16:15,743 --> 00:16:17,664
Say we were speaking out of ill-will.

147
00:16:18,466 --> 00:16:19,807
We say something nasty.

148
00:16:20,850 --> 00:16:27,138
We might feel powerful as a result, but since all things fall apart, sooner or later we feel vulnerable again.

149
00:16:27,197 --> 00:16:29,660
How do we get back to power?

150
00:16:30,501 --> 00:16:32,303
Find someone we can vent our anger on.

151
00:16:33,285 --> 00:16:35,227
So we get in the habit of nasty speech.

152
00:16:36,269 --> 00:16:37,291
Where does this lead us?

153
00:16:38,272 --> 00:16:40,434
We lose friends and gain enemies.

154
00:16:41,090 --> 00:16:51,870
Out of fear, some people might rally around us, but their suppressed feelings get in the way of real friendship, and most will be delighted to stab us in the back when they get the opportunity.

155
00:16:53,332 --> 00:16:58,962
A bully lives in a state of suppressed fear that his own deeds will be perpetrated on him.

156
00:17:00,529 --> 00:17:11,607
Similarly for greed, the enjoyment is temporary while the stress of continually needing to consume is exhausting, while overconsumption itself can harm our bodies.

157
00:17:13,151 --> 00:17:18,339
And everything we consume has to be paid for, so we get stressed out with overwork.

158
00:17:19,401 --> 00:17:23,989
Satiating greed makes us feel needy rather than satisfied.

159
00:17:26,567 --> 00:17:33,837
Delusion manifests in the myriad untested assumptions we make that let us ignore what doesn't serve our agenda.

160
00:17:35,380 --> 00:17:39,905
We might take our family and friends for granted assume they will always be there for us.

161
00:17:40,948 --> 00:17:47,115
If one of them suddenly dies or emigrates we might get quite a shock to find how much we needed them.

162
00:17:48,258 --> 00:17:53,384
We may have many regrets about how little we appreciated their company and support.

163
00:17:55,390 --> 00:18:04,305
On the other hand, if we think, speak or act out of generosity, goodwill or wisdom, the law of karma tells us that we will reap the benefits.

164
00:18:05,787 --> 00:18:15,323
There will be social benefits as everyone prefers people who are generous rather than stingy, caring rather than unkind, wise rather than foolish.

165
00:18:15,640 --> 00:18:21,568
Also, the benefits go deep within us, as each kind word helps heal our own heart.

166
00:18:22,490 --> 00:18:26,496
Each act of generosity counters our sense of neediness.

167
00:18:27,438 --> 00:18:30,962
Each wise thought undermines our ignorance and delusion.

168
00:18:33,366 --> 00:18:39,015
It is the motivation that matters for the law of kamma, not the act itself.

169
00:18:39,333 --> 00:18:47,882
If a doctor cares for his patients only because he gets well paid, he won't reap the benefits of kindness, but will suffer the consequences of greed.

170
00:18:48,803 --> 00:18:58,652
Similarly, if our efforts to solve a conflict end up making it worse, we won't suffer any karmic harm, so long as our motivation was good.

171
00:19:00,734 --> 00:19:08,142
Sila, the second stage of the Eightfold Path, is therefore not a simple matter of following rules for good behaviour.

172
00:19:09,758 --> 00:19:12,119
We also need to examine our motivation.

173
00:19:13,642 --> 00:19:15,623
Often we are aware of mixed motives.

174
00:19:16,183 --> 00:19:21,167
We know we are angry, but we still feel it would be best to confront the person who angered us.

175
00:19:22,429 --> 00:19:25,791
Which seeds are we nourishing here, ill will or wisdom?

176
00:19:27,713 --> 00:19:38,584
We can consciously make a suitable good wish like, may this do more good than harm, may I learn from any mistakes I make, to help us move in the right direction.

177
00:19:41,112 --> 00:19:47,780
The Buddha divides Sila into three sections, right speech, right action and right livelihood.

178
00:19:49,403 --> 00:19:51,326
Right speech has four aspects.

179
00:19:52,007 --> 00:19:58,957
It must be truthful, timely and useful, as well as being said gently rather than harshly.

180
00:20:00,338 --> 00:20:02,781
Let's see how each of these leads to happiness.

181
00:20:05,185 --> 00:20:09,751
Truthfulness in the long run is easier on our psyche than lying.

182
00:20:10,221 --> 00:20:14,391
Probably the most usual way we lie is to exaggerate things for effect.

183
00:20:15,933 --> 00:20:22,386
If we lie or exaggerate, there's always a danger of being caught out, which leads to restlessness and worry.

184
00:20:23,348 --> 00:20:30,103
Apart from that, others come to distrust and disrespect us to some extent, which can limit their friendships.

185
00:20:32,125 --> 00:20:36,509
Speech is useful from the point of view of Scylla if it promotes happiness.

186
00:20:37,670 --> 00:20:42,234
Friendly greetings are useful and small talk can also help us feel at ease.

187
00:20:43,415 --> 00:20:46,558
The main temptation towards unhelpful speech is gossiping.

188
00:20:46,598 --> 00:20:53,325
To gossip is to talk about the doings of third parties, often feeding on their misfortune.

189
00:20:54,625 --> 00:20:58,690
It can easily spread rumours and allow unchallenged backbiting.

190
00:21:00,339 --> 00:21:03,143
I remember a neighbour telling me about a couple who had broken up.

191
00:21:04,243 --> 00:21:08,567
They had been building a house extension to their house when the wife ran away with the builder.

192
00:21:09,489 --> 00:21:18,018
It might have been funny in a Hollywood movie, and the grin on her face told me she was seeing it in this light, not feeling for the family and the pain this would be causing.

193
00:21:20,359 --> 00:21:28,288
Sometimes it can be difficult to draw the line between gossip, small talk and the genuine need to discuss a third party's behaviour.

194
00:21:29,872 --> 00:21:33,458
During friendly chatter we often mention news of people we know in common.

195
00:21:34,378 --> 00:21:39,166
Ask yourself, how would I feel if this person was listening to our conversation?

196
00:21:40,548 --> 00:21:45,196
If you would feel any way embarrassed, it's likely that your talk has strayed into gossip.

197
00:21:47,184 --> 00:21:53,332
On the other hand, if we've been hurt by someone, it often helps to discuss the matter with a third party.

198
00:21:54,212 --> 00:22:00,901
Keeping it all to ourselves for fear of generating the karma of wrong speech is not always the wisest course.

199
00:22:02,061 --> 00:22:06,406
We often need the help of a friend or counsellor to move towards forgiveness.

200
00:22:09,631 --> 00:22:16,077
The motivation here is not to gossip, but to clarify our thoughts and let our heart heal through sympathy.

201
00:22:17,340 --> 00:22:21,950
Basically we're asking our friend or therapist for help in bearing the difficulty.

202
00:22:23,531 --> 00:22:26,557
We could see it as an extension of mindfulness practice.

203
00:22:27,740 --> 00:22:31,586
In mindfulness we let our angry thoughts crash through our psyche.

204
00:22:32,028 --> 00:22:33,550
He did this, she did that.

205
00:22:34,132 --> 00:22:36,316
I can't understand how they didn't notice.

206
00:22:37,999 --> 00:22:40,564
Eventually anger wears itself out.

207
00:22:41,489 --> 00:22:47,356
Letting these angry thoughts be heard by a friend or therapist brings the matter to a new level of consciousness.

208
00:22:48,778 --> 00:22:55,607
The shared awareness allows a bigger space for the anger to express itself and for the futility of anger to be acknowledged.

209
00:22:57,069 --> 00:23:02,096
Often the process can help turn our hearts towards understanding and forgiveness.

210
00:23:05,434 --> 00:23:09,734
Timely speech is especially important when we have something difficult to say.

211
00:23:09,795 --> 00:23:13,571
Suppose we feel hurt by a friend's behaviour.

212
00:23:14,834 --> 00:23:20,602
If we see their despondent, harassed or preoccupied by something else, best hold back.

213
00:23:21,762 --> 00:23:24,547
It's so easy for negativity to spread like a virus.

214
00:23:25,587 --> 00:23:35,040
What was intended to restore friendship, despondency might translate into rejection, while harassment might see as yet another injustice.

215
00:23:35,981 --> 00:23:42,951
Best ask them to meet to discuss something a bit sensitive, so that they will be more prepared for a genuine heart-to-heart conversation.

216
00:23:45,125 --> 00:23:50,993
Harsh speech adds cutting words or a hurtful tone to whatever message we need to give.

217
00:23:52,135 --> 00:23:56,363
In the short term, this might make us feel more powerful, in control.

218
00:23:56,423 --> 00:24:03,775
But it often provokes the other into a riposte, and an argument can easily break out.

219
00:24:03,755 --> 00:24:10,711
Even if the other doesn't react but is crushed by our remark, we've lost some degree of their friendship.

220
00:24:11,491 --> 00:24:21,273
So in the long run, caring speech promotes our own happiness, while harsh speech leads us to the unhappiness and social isolation of the bully.

221
00:24:24,780 --> 00:24:27,243
Right action has three components.

222
00:24:28,244 --> 00:24:34,071
To refrain from harming others, stealing their property and misusing our sexuality.

223
00:24:35,752 --> 00:24:38,876
The greatest harm we can do to another is to take their life.

224
00:24:40,259 --> 00:24:46,806
The Buddha doesn't confine this precept to human life and many Buddhists would also be vegetarian for this reason.

225
00:24:47,596 --> 00:24:50,628
However, the Buddha didn't forbid his disciples to eat meat.

226
00:24:51,412 --> 00:24:57,538
This was probably pragmatic, for they had to survive on alms rounds, so had to accept whatever they were given.

227
00:24:59,932 --> 00:25:09,592
While most of us would not want to kill or harm others we can take this precept further by asking ourselves what we could do to promote others welfare.

228
00:25:10,855 --> 00:25:18,852
Purchasing ethically produced goods would be one avenue giving to charities which combat poverty would be another.

229
00:25:19,372 --> 00:25:30,644
We can also look after animal welfare as best we can, avoiding factory farmed produce for example, because of the horrendous suffering involved, or becoming vegetarians.

230
00:25:31,865 --> 00:25:35,871
Vegans take this a step further and avoid all animal products.

231
00:25:36,612 --> 00:25:46,222
This prevents much suffering, for example the separation of calf from cow at the moment of birth, so that we can take the cow's milk for our dairy products.

232
00:25:48,193 --> 00:25:52,318
Moving on to the second component of right action, not stealing.

233
00:25:54,141 --> 00:25:57,084
Few people who come and retreat would be involved in gross theft.

234
00:25:57,884 --> 00:26:03,151
But we can take this further to ask whether we are using more than our fair share of the earth's resources.

235
00:26:04,251 --> 00:26:09,017
Even governments now agree that human activities are adding to the problem of climate change.

236
00:26:09,958 --> 00:26:17,626
The effect is already being felt in many developing countries and threatens homes and livelihoods as well as food and water supplies.

237
00:26:19,176 --> 00:26:23,162
Consumption of fossil fuel is a major component driving climate change.

238
00:26:24,303 --> 00:26:29,209
When we take a flight or drive, rather than use public transport, we add to the problem.

239
00:26:30,590 --> 00:26:34,516
Every manufactured item we purchase adds to our carbon footprint.

240
00:26:35,758 --> 00:26:45,690
We need to regularly ask ourselves whether our energy consumption is justified or whether we're frivolously flitting away the Earth's resources and fueling climate change.

241
00:26:49,281 --> 00:26:53,647
The third component of right action is not to abuse our sexuality.

242
00:26:55,029 --> 00:26:59,116
Sexuality gives joy that can nourish and sustain a loving relationship.

243
00:27:00,157 --> 00:27:05,665
But if it is used frivolously or to gain power over another, it can lead to a lot of suffering.

244
00:27:07,269 --> 00:27:10,773
Infidelity can cause enormous hurt and break up relationships.

245
00:27:12,256 --> 00:27:18,444
Abortion is surely suffering from the fetus's point of view and very often from the mother's view as well.

246
00:27:19,538 --> 00:27:25,507
and we have the horrors of childhood sexual abuse and vulnerable people being forced into prostitution.

247
00:27:28,351 --> 00:27:43,233
While many of us will not have to face the suffering of abortion, sexual abuse or forced prostitution, we do have to face many challenges in maintaining this precept within a society where sex outside of committed relationship is quite common.

248
00:27:44,362 --> 00:27:51,478
The main question to keep in mind are, could this lead to hurt or other harm for myself or others?

249
00:27:52,760 --> 00:27:55,366
Will it lead to happiness for myself or others?

250
00:27:58,115 --> 00:28:02,660
The final strand of morality in the Eightfold Path is right livelihood.

251
00:28:03,721 --> 00:28:06,522
We need to be sure our livelihood is not harming others.

252
00:28:07,785 --> 00:28:19,737
The livelihoods the Buddha listed as wrong were those dealing with weapons, poisons, slavery, including buying and selling children and prostitution, intoxicants and meat.

253
00:28:20,917 --> 00:28:27,884
Weapons, poison, slavery and butchery can obviously kill and harm, while intoxicants promote delusion.

254
00:28:30,328 --> 00:28:35,395
Few people would argue with the advice not to have anything to do with slavery or forced prostitution.

255
00:28:36,357 --> 00:28:38,540
The harm these do is beyond question.

256
00:28:39,803 --> 00:28:48,756
But the other areas mentioned here are tolerated in our society, making this a very challenging aspect of the Eightfold Path for those already employed in one of these.

257
00:28:50,218 --> 00:28:56,386
Although few poisons are sold legally nowadays, there is the tricky area of pest control.

258
00:28:57,311 --> 00:29:02,157
If your work involves dealing with these, see whether you could stock a compassionate alternative.

259
00:29:03,259 --> 00:29:09,367
For example, there are rat and mouse traps that do not kill the animal, and also alternatives for dealing with slugs.

260
00:29:11,590 --> 00:29:19,101
Butchery obviously involves great suffering for animals, and very often there are long, frightening journeys involved before slaughter.

261
00:29:20,380 --> 00:29:29,390
To be directly involved in this must be an incredible challenge to a sensitive heart and can only foster cruelty and indifference.

262
00:29:29,410 --> 00:29:32,792
Rearing animals for slaughter is part of these same business.

263
00:29:35,696 --> 00:29:46,167
The Buddha's unequivocal advice is to get out of this aspect of farming and anything else to do with the meat trade for your own spiritual welfare as well as the welfare of animals.

264
00:29:49,134 --> 00:29:55,103
Many people are employed in the weapons industry, from soldiers on the ground to scientists in the lab.

265
00:29:56,664 --> 00:30:01,270
So much war seems pointless and horrific when seen from a distance or with hindsight.

266
00:30:02,332 --> 00:30:08,780
Who, in hindsight, could justify the atrocities of the First World War, the Vietnamese War?

267
00:30:09,487 --> 00:30:14,715
but many would argue that it was justified in the Second World War in order to prevent the rise of Hitler.

268
00:30:15,998 --> 00:30:23,731
In 1995, over 8,000 people were massacred in Srebrenica as the UN stood by.

269
00:30:24,623 --> 00:30:28,828
Was the UN right not to attack the invading Serbs in order to defend these civilians?

270
00:30:30,211 --> 00:30:31,551
These are hard questions.

271
00:30:32,773 --> 00:30:38,422
In war, each side justifies their action, seeing the enemy as the greater threat to humanity.

272
00:30:39,864 --> 00:30:43,327
But can you stand by as atrocities are committed?

273
00:30:44,569 --> 00:30:49,737
Would it be justified to kill the guards of a concentration camp in order to liberate those within?

274
00:30:51,606 --> 00:30:53,390
There are no easy answers here.

275
00:30:53,450 --> 00:30:56,976
It's a question of choosing the lesser of evils.

276
00:30:58,117 --> 00:31:01,865
Certainly a soldier's life is not to be envied from the point of view of karma.

277
00:31:03,027 --> 00:31:08,957
It would need the wisdom of a Buddha to choose the most compassionate response in such a situation.

278
00:31:11,401 --> 00:31:20,173
Bhante has an essay, Is Armed Intervention Ever Justified?, on the Satipanya website, which explores this in more depth.

279
00:31:21,214 --> 00:31:27,944
He distinguishes between force and violence, which helps us clarify Sila in our response to the question of war.

280
00:31:30,608 --> 00:31:36,597
His essay also cites wonderful exemplars of the non-violent approach to conflict management.

281
00:31:37,777 --> 00:31:43,082
Great leaders like Nelson Mandela and Gandhi brokered peace for warlike situations.

282
00:31:44,223 --> 00:31:52,011
And figures like Aung San Suu Kyi and Dalai Lama inspire us to look only for a peaceful solution.

283
00:31:54,855 --> 00:32:04,964
The injunction not to deal with intoxicants poses hard questions for many people, as almost every shop, restaurant and hotel is expected to supply alcohol.

284
00:32:06,515 --> 00:32:12,963
If we can change job, then best do this, but if not, do we make ourselves redundant to avoid this problem?

285
00:32:14,145 --> 00:32:15,988
What about the consequences for our family?

286
00:32:16,048 --> 00:32:19,212
Would the harm to them be justified?

287
00:32:20,474 --> 00:32:27,003
Our culture makes it easy for us to justify alcohol, and most of us know people who live good lives while drinking moderately.

288
00:32:28,182 --> 00:32:35,297
On the other hand, many road accidents are alcohol-related, as well as domestic and street violence and sexual abuse.

289
00:32:36,839 --> 00:32:41,710
Our cultural ease with alcohol also facilitates alcoholism with all its problems.

290
00:32:43,031 --> 00:32:48,282
And if we're interested in liberation, can it ever help to cloud our mind with alcohol?

291
00:32:51,232 --> 00:32:54,777
As I think you will agree, Sila is not an easy matter.

292
00:32:55,878 --> 00:33:01,265
For each of us there will be difficult ethical questions to face at some stage in life.

293
00:33:03,307 --> 00:33:10,977
We need a clear mind to find the appropriate response in complex situations and a stout heart to meet the challenge.

294
00:33:12,679 --> 00:33:20,008
The last section of the Eightfold Path concerns the cultivation of mind and heart in meditation practice.

295
00:33:23,042 --> 00:33:25,626
Let's first take a look to review our progress.

296
00:33:27,349 --> 00:33:33,779
We hacked out a clearing using the sword of wisdom with its double blade, right understanding and right attitude.

297
00:33:34,740 --> 00:33:39,828
We stepped into the clearing as we brought wisdom into our speech, action and livelihood.

298
00:33:41,171 --> 00:33:49,944
Now we need to rest a while, assess our new surroundings, polish our sword of wisdom before we tackle the thicket again.

299
00:33:52,337 --> 00:33:56,082
This section of the pass also has three strands.

300
00:33:58,766 --> 00:34:03,030
Right effort, right mindfulness and right concentration.

301
00:34:05,834 --> 00:34:10,539
Right effort involves the factor of energy that we met in the factor of enlightenment.

302
00:34:11,280 --> 00:34:15,105
So here we have again the leading trio in our wild geese.

303
00:34:16,434 --> 00:34:22,222
To see their interrelation, we have the analogy of three children wanting to pick some flowers from a tree.

304
00:34:22,282 --> 00:34:41,768
None of them is tall enough to reach the flowers, so the strongest one, right effort, bends over to let the tallest one, right concentration, stand on his back, while the steadiest of the three, right mindfulness, provides a shoulder for him to lean on.

305
00:34:43,012 --> 00:34:50,139
Supported by right effort, balanced by mindfulness, concentration can then pluck the flowers.

306
00:34:52,422 --> 00:34:57,728
Now this image isn't quite in accord with our image of the wild geese which had mindfulness in the lead.

307
00:34:58,789 --> 00:35:04,695
But they can come together if we still see mindfulness as the leader, just not the tallest.

308
00:35:05,996 --> 00:35:12,041
Mindfulness tells concentration to draw back if he is overreaching, unbalancing the trio.

309
00:35:13,438 --> 00:35:23,590
When mindfulness is happy that the trio are well balanced, it is the ability of our minds to focus on whatever is taking our attention that lets the Dhamma clarify for us.

310
00:35:27,635 --> 00:35:34,744
Right effort involves all the energy and resolution we bring to our meditation practice.

311
00:35:34,764 --> 00:35:39,210
The Buddha delineates right effort into four components.

312
00:35:39,949 --> 00:35:53,153
to prevent unwholesome states from arising, to let go of those that have already arisen, to encourage new wholesome states and to perfect those that have already arisen.

313
00:35:56,280 --> 00:36:02,851
The effort we make to maintain moment to moment awareness prevents unwholesome states from arising.

314
00:36:04,164 --> 00:36:13,315
If we can maintain awareness at the level of sense contact and feeling, the hindrances don't get a chance to blossom and spread their seeds.

315
00:36:14,657 --> 00:36:17,800
This carries out the first component of right effort.

316
00:36:21,204 --> 00:36:25,869
The second component involves the effort we make to hold attention steady on dukkha.

317
00:36:27,050 --> 00:36:31,135
This allows us let go of hindrances that already cloud our consciousness.

318
00:36:32,313 --> 00:36:38,983
As we notice the transitory, uncontrollable nature of pleasure and pain, we undermine desire.

319
00:36:39,025 --> 00:36:43,873
Working with aversion brings us to the edge of our comfort zone.

320
00:36:45,436 --> 00:36:52,847
Right effort allows us to hold attention there till the boundary starts to dissolve, and we realize it was all illusion.

321
00:36:54,090 --> 00:36:56,193
Really, there was nothing to fear or hate.

322
00:36:58,199 --> 00:37:10,552
Our efforts to stir energy through physical exercise and mental resolution undermine dullness and lethargy, while the effort to centre attention on some calming focus undermines restlessness.

323
00:37:12,355 --> 00:37:19,121
As we stir the factor of investigation, we clarify the Dhamma for ourselves, undermining doubt.

324
00:37:22,445 --> 00:37:27,851
The third component of right effort involves encouraging wholesome states to manifest.

325
00:37:28,996 --> 00:37:33,641
This also results from the effort we make to maintain mindfulness in meditation.

326
00:37:35,063 --> 00:37:46,579
For example, all seven of the factors of enlightenment are being developed and perfected and these transmute into the five spiritual faculties to help us through daily life.

327
00:37:51,927 --> 00:37:58,074
The final component involves the effort we make in practicing metta and the other Brahma-viharas.

328
00:37:59,286 --> 00:38:08,942
These bring our wholesome states to perfection.

329
00:38:09,496 --> 00:38:17,628
We bring bare attention to our sensory experience including the sixth sense of our mind with its feelings, emotions and thoughts.

330
00:38:18,710 --> 00:38:20,612
We sense any reactions to these.

331
00:38:21,954 --> 00:38:25,019
Desire trying to wrap us around pleasant feelings.

332
00:38:26,101 --> 00:38:28,664
Aversion trying to push away unpleasant feelings.

333
00:38:29,786 --> 00:38:35,114
Delusion trying to shut out physical sensations for the sake of a mental pleasure world.

334
00:38:37,153 --> 00:38:46,775
Sensing the pain of reactivity, wisdom persuades us to relax again, to let pleasant and unpleasant sensations be just as they are.

335
00:38:48,831 --> 00:38:57,400
Concentration, the final strand of the eightfold path, describes the mind's ability to focus, like looking through a telescope.

336
00:38:58,380 --> 00:39:04,588
It brings stillness to the mind by unifying it with undistracted focus on whatever calls attention.

337
00:39:05,849 --> 00:39:17,099
Increasingly, what calls attention is dukkha and what causes it, as well as the opposite side of the coin, the absence of dukkha and the conditions that foster this.

338
00:39:17,079 --> 00:39:25,931
In other words, it is the Four Noble Truths that interest us, and their manifestation and our experience is what calls attention.

339
00:39:28,856 --> 00:39:42,175
At times the hindrances are kept in check by the factors of enlightenment, and we sense a current of ease running underneath our usual sense of experience, our being tiptoes towards the mystery.

340
00:39:43,577 --> 00:39:45,940
What is the experience of ease?

341
00:39:47,083 --> 00:39:50,992
What would be left of us if there was no urge driving us into action?

342
00:39:52,577 --> 00:40:06,088
We become more familiar with the seeming absence of our usual self, with the fluid, changing, unsatisfying nature of the reality we inhabit, and the quiet mystery that runs beneath.

343
00:40:08,751 --> 00:40:20,362
This focus is only possible on the back of right effort our efforts not to grasp at the temporary pleasures of the world and to cultivate instead the qualities that sustain our meditation.

344
00:40:21,784 --> 00:40:33,795
And it needs the leadership of mindfulness the reminder to relax our focus whenever mindfulness senses that new seeds of grasping or aversion are sprouting up.

345
00:40:33,815 --> 00:40:38,099
It's easy for these to sprout as we gaze beyond our usual boundaries.

346
00:40:38,958 --> 00:40:51,739
We get confused or frightened, restless or dull, or so deeply desiring the end of suffering that we cloud our minds with attachment to progress and aversion to whatever seems to be getting in our way.

347
00:40:54,625 --> 00:40:58,271
The Buddha's promise is that one day the turmoil will end.

348
00:40:59,634 --> 00:41:02,940
We will satisfy our desire for the end of suffering.

349
00:41:04,489 --> 00:41:10,318
With that we will know for ourselves what remains when all desire fades away.

350
00:41:13,945 --> 00:41:15,909
A quick recap before finishing.

351
00:41:17,570 --> 00:41:19,313
The path starts with wisdom.

352
00:41:20,836 --> 00:41:28,489
Lost in the jungle of ignorance, we ponder the Buddha's teaching to get an inkling of what causes suffering and what relieves it.

353
00:41:29,835 --> 00:41:35,003
As the truth sinks into our heart, our attitude to the world grows friendlier.

354
00:41:35,043 --> 00:41:43,016
The jungle doesn't seem quite so impenetrable, and the sword of wisdom cuts through delusion to form a clearing.

355
00:41:44,440 --> 00:41:55,016
Here, sila blossoms in the form of right speech, action and livelihood, to be rewarded by the law of karma, opening our hearts to happiness.

356
00:41:56,465 --> 00:42:01,132
We rest a while in the clearing to cultivate our heart and mind in meditation.

357
00:42:02,693 --> 00:42:05,498
We make the effort needed to maintain mindfulness.

358
00:42:07,161 --> 00:42:18,137
Supported by effort, led and balanced by mindfulness, our mind focuses on the Dhamma and we learn the Four Noble Truths for ourselves.

359
00:42:19,739 --> 00:42:25,306
This sharpens the sword of wisdom, the first strands of the Eightfold Path.

360
00:42:26,164 --> 00:42:34,635
Step by step, the Eightfold Path leads us from the jungle of ignorance to the freedom of enlightenment.

361
00:42:38,561 --> 00:42:42,206
I hope this reflection on the Fourth Noble Truth has been helpful.

362
00:42:43,688 --> 00:42:49,876
May we and all beings follow the Eightfold Path to the end of suffering.

